-- 5. GitHub Copilot - code-AI head-term, peer-double for cursor S133/codeium S141/cody S185/copilot-microsoft S141/continue-dev S186/tabnine S181
('github-copilot', 'GitHub Copilot',
'AI code completion from GitHub and OpenAI, the original mainstream code AI since 2021.',
'GitHub Copilot is the original mainstream AI code assistant, launched as a Technical Preview in June 2021 and reaching general availability in June 2022. Built by GitHub in partnership with OpenAI on the Codex model, then upgraded through GPT-3.5, GPT-4, and now multiple frontier models including Claude 3.5 Sonnet and GPT-4o in the model picker, Copilot now spans inline code suggestions, multi-line block completion, Copilot Chat for inline questions and code generation, Copilot Workspace for full task planning with multi-file edits, Copilot for Pull Requests for review summaries and auto-generated descriptions, and Copilot for CLI for terminal command suggestions. IDE support covers VS Code (deepest integration), JetBrains IntelliJ family, Neovim, Visual Studio, and Xcode beta. Pricing: free for verified students, open source maintainers, and teachers via GitHub Education; Individual at 10 USD per month or 100 USD per year; Business at 19 USD per seat per month with admin controls and IP indemnification; Enterprise at 39 USD per seat with policy management and Copilot Chat in github.com. Cursor competes on deeper agentic IDE features in a fork of VS Code, Codeium on a strong free tier, Cody from Sourcegraph on enterprise codebase context, Continue on open source self-hosting. For most developers in 2026, GitHub Copilot is still the default starter pick because of native GitHub integration, IDE breadth, and enterprise IP indemnification.',
'', 'https://github.com/features/copilot', 'https://github.com/features/copilot',
'freemium', true, 10, 4.6, 9800,
false, false, false,
ARRAY['code-ai', 'ai-assistants'],
ARRAY['Original mainstream code AI with the broadest IDE support (VS Code, JetBrains, Neovim, Visual Studio)',
'Model picker now includes Claude 3.5 Sonnet, GPT-4o, and other frontier models',
'Free for verified students, open source maintainers, and teachers via GitHub Education',
